title: For Sale/Trade:  Great Gun from the Great War: British Enfield No.1 MkIII*
postcontent: This collectable but very shootable .303 British WWI Enfield is dated 1918 and made by Standard Small Arms in the UK.  It was part of the "peddle scheme," where a Birmingham company contracted out for parts made throughout Great Britian and would assemble them at its factory. It worked, but not as well as hoped, making this a collectable Enfield, as well as a good shooter. Rifle is in great shape, very good bore, no rust, no pitting, good bluing, wood was degreased, oiled and waxed. Holding this is holding history: made for the war to end all wars and then used again in WWII. title: For Sale:  Jaeger made Custom Mauser in 6mm Lee Navy(6mm U.S.N. or .236 Navy)
postcontent:
A very attractive Jaeger made Mauser in 6mm Lee Navy(6mm U.S.N. or .236 Navy)

It has a Mannlicher stock made of very attractive Tiger Stripe Maple. Sorry, my photos don't do the stock justice. When I turned my flash on to try and bring out the grain of the wood the glare from the flash was worse.
This rifle was my Grandfather's. He grew up in Philadephia near Jaeger's shop (in Jenkintown PA, a suburb of Philadelphia.)

At the time my Grandfather had this rifle made he considered this to be one of the best available varmint rounds, he handloaded rounds that he said were devastating on the local groundhog population. (the time was pre-WWII)
The action is marked "Spandau 1916", a K98 Mauser action. This rifle has no other markings on it. I know that typically Jaeger would stamp all of his rifles with his name. I don't know why in this case he did not do that with this rifle. This rifle would have been made very early on in Jaeger's career, he is mostly known for his custom work after WWII. I am unaware of any of his stamped custom rifles made before WWII. Jaeger's shop did the barreling of the action, trigger work, sight mounting, etc. Since my grandfather is not around to ask I can only guess why it was not stamped. My grandfather was a teenager when he had this rifle made up for him. Perhaps he did not want the rifle to have any extra markings on it (my grandfather was that type of guy). My guess is it was a combination of the those two thing. But I just don't know. The rifle is very nicely made and has lots of nice details, even the screws that hold the scope mount have engraved letters on them, not stamped, to show which is the front and rear screw. Great detail all over.

The wrist of this rifle has a crack in it that runs with the grain.

It does not seem to affect the structure of the stock, the stock is very sturdy, but visually you can see it.

It has a peep sight installed and drilled for a scope mount, the period scope mount is included.
This rifle is a great package that shows what a well funded youth would get as a varmint rifle pre-WWII.

I have many additional photos available. Send me an email and I would be happy to email you photos.
All offers are welcome and encouraged. Please don't hesitate to contact me.

I will ship this rifle to anywhere in the US for $50, which INCLUDES a hard rifle case that it will be shipped in.

Sorry, no returns. I am not an FFL and can't directly receive a return. I would be happy to email you any additional photos so you know exactly what you are buying.

All offers are welcome and encouraged.

REDACTED

postcontent:
https://www.extreme-impact-ammo.com/index.php?l=product_detail&p=59

The .454 Casull is one cartridge that Buffalo Bore Ammunition does not load to it's full pressure limit. When loaded to it's full pressure potential the .454 Casull can become unreliable and unpleasant to shoot. At upper pressure levels, heavy bullets tend to jump crimp - tying up the cylinder. (wouldn't this be great in an emergency) Also, fired brass can stick in the chambers. 

Buffalo Bore Ammunition feels that a 360 gr. bullet (or 325 gr. bullet at 1525 fps) at 1425 fps is still very powerful, comfortable to shoot, and TOTALLY RELIABLE. At these levels, these bullets give up nothing in killing performance.
